availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: This document sets out the terms of an agreement between An Calbhach Ó Domhnaill (d. 1566) and Giolla Easbuig Mac Cailin, 5th Earl of Argyll (1538–1575). It was written in 1560 in Early Modern Gaelic by an accomplished scribe. The scribe is anonymous and the place of writing is unknown; it could have been drawn up in either Ulster or Argyll. However, as the agreement would in any case have needed to have been in language that was accessible to both parties, it remains a valuable source for Gaelic administrative and legal literacy among elites of the period. It is also a particularly rich source of vocabulary on politics, military organization, and seafaring.

summary.p: The only text in this manuscript is the Argyll-O'Donnell Agreement, written in Early Modern Gaelic in 1560. It is a legal document, setting out and renewing the terms of a previous agreement reached by An Calbhach with the previous Earl of Argyll (Giolla Easbuig Mac Cailin, 4th Earl of Argyll, 1498–1558) in 1555, under which An Calbhach would receive military aid in exchange for an annual payment and the billeting of Argyll's troops in his lands in Ireland. An Calbhach required military aid as he was trying to wrest control of the lordship of Tír Conaill from his father, Maghnus. The agreement is presumably being renewed because, by 1560, (a) An Calbhach had obtained the lordship of Tír Conaill and (b) there was a new Earl of Argyll. All other documents relating to the 1555 agreement are now lost.

The person or persons responsible for drawing up the present document are unknown and the scribe is anonymous. While it could have been composed in either Argyll or Ulster, as Argyll is the dominant party in the relationship, one might suspect that he or his agents would have been the major influence on the terms of the agreement. In any case, the language must have been comprehensible to him and to the various officials in Argyll who might have needed to familiarise themselves with its terms.

msItem.title: Argyll-O'Donnell Agreement
msItem.note: The text of the agreement has been edited and translated from the present manuscript by MacKechnie (1953). It has been commented on by, among others, Black (2012, 2016).

physDesc.p: MS33 is in near-perfect physical condition, with complete legibility throughout. One scribe (Hand58) writes the text of the contract. Another (Hand60) writes out the witness list and a third (Hand61) writes Ó Domhnaill’s signature. The contract is presented as a single paragraph. The witness list is split into two paragraphs (fol. 1ra and 1rc) on either side of Ó Domhnaill’s signature (fol. 1rb). No headings or marginalia appear.

summary.p: As noted above, it is not whether the treaty was drawn up in Argyll or Ulster, although it seems likely that Earl of Argyll or his agents would have had the predominant influence on the content. The present document bears the signature of Ó Domhnaill but not that of Argyll and the day and month have been left blank. This suggests that it was intended to be Argyll's eventual copy, which would have been signed by Ó Domhnaill and then sent to Argyll to be both signed and retained by him. However, for some reason, the ratification process was left incomplete as far as this document is concerned. Various transcriptions, translations (one contemporary with the agreement), and abstracts derived from this version (MS33) are reportedly to be found among the Argyll Papers (Black 2016: 55–56) at Inveraray. Further study of these might elucidate the provenance and status of the present document further. Otherwise, it is first attested as being at Inveraray in the late 19th century, as it was studied by the 10th Duke of Argyll.

langUsage.p: The language of the agreement is largely conformant to the conventions of literary Early Modern Gaelic. There are some conservative features, such as preserved accusatives, although no archaisms like infixed pronouns. This is roughly what would be expected from the text of a formal, high-status document of this period, even if it does also have a practical purpose. In terms of orthography and even morphology, there are some potential signs of Scottish Gaelic influence (e.g. spread of dental declension endings, some of which have been devoiced from /γ/ to /χ/; devoicing of /γ/ to /χ/ elsewhere; possible orthographic evidence of pre-aspiration). However, they are for the most part also equally explicable as features of a northern dialect of Irish. Consideration of language and orthography unfortunately does not enable us to move beyond Black’s (2017: 6) view that “there is only a 50% chance that that scribe was provided by Argyll rather than O’Donnell”.
